Haskell -<p><pre><code>  fizzbuzz x = case (x `mod` 3, x `mod` 5) of
      (0, 0) -> &quot;FizzBuzz&quot;
      (0, _) -> &quot;Fizz&quot;
      (_, 0) -> &quot;Buzz&quot;
       _     -> show i

  mapM_ (putStrLn . fizzbuzz) [1..100]</code></pre>

Python doesn&#x27;t have pattern matching but the code is basically the same. I guess better cases for showing off the feature are ones where the patterns aren&#x27;t just True/False tuples.<p><pre><code>    for i in range (1, 101):
    	fbsign = (i % 3 == 0, i % 5 == 0)
	if fbsign == (1, 1): print(&quot;Fizzbuzz&quot;)
	elif fbsign == (1, 0): print(&quot;Fizz&quot;)
	elif fbsign == (0, 1): print(&quot;Buzz&quot;)
	else: print(i)</code></pre>
